<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOPICS / ARCHITECTURE; PASADENA COMPLEX WINS BEAUTIFICATION AWARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After four years and $90 million in renovations, one Colorado Boulevard 
shopping complex has won the Los Angeles Business Council's Beautification 
Award in the historical renovation/adaptive reuse category. 
</P>
<P>
 The complex in Old Pasadena has 23 businesses, ranging from bookstores and art 
galleries to clothing stores and restaurants, as well as the city's first jail, 
general store and City Hall, which date back to the late 19th Century. 
</P>
<P>
 An outdoor courtyard with sculptures and benches was created from back alleys 
and brick doors. "It was generic space," said Scott Bates, an architect who 
worked on the complex. "But outdoor spaces are just as important as indoor 
spaces in Southern California. So we designed a place where people can eat and 
relax." 
</P>
<P>
 The council, which consists of various Los Angeles businesses, has awarded 
annual beautification certificates since 1970 to recognize and promote the 
architecture, landscapes and historical renovations in Los Angeles County. 
</P>
</TEXT>
