<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hicks and Len Hall 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 HAPPY ENDING: A group of junior lifeguards visiting here from New Zealand, the 
victims of thieves last weekend, found themselves among friends after all. 
After learning about the theft of the teen-agers' airline tickets, Sharon 
Pettit of Cypress, the wife of a United Airlines exec, got him to replace all 
the tickets -- free. Passports will be replaced by the New Zealand Embassy -- 
free. . . . "What started as a sad story turned out to really impress our 
guests," says Kara Johan of Orange, from one of the host families. 
</P>
<P>
 TRAVELING REX: One thing Americans and Russians have in common is a 
fascination with dinosaurs. Nearly 10,000 visitors a day have been wandering 
among the 17 robotic, life-size prehistoric replicas in Moscow's Sokolniki 
Park. The animated dinosaurs were created by Dinamation of Irvine, which is 
hitting 100 cities worldwide with such exhibits this year. . . . The Russian 
exhibit runs until Sept. 10. Says Dinamation founder Chris Mays: "We're proud 
to . . . bring smiles to the Russian people." 
</P>
<P>
 CHRISTY'S MAN: This month's Esquire magazine cover shows Christie Brinkley 
topless, but appropriately covered by a copy of Henry Kissinger's latest book, 
"Diplomacy." But is it autographed? . . . You can get the former secretary of 
state to sign one for you next Wednesday. He's kicking off the Distinguished 
Authors series at the Richard Nixon Library & Birthplace -- and signing some 
books. But library policy: He won't sign unless you buy it there. 
</P>
<P>
 THE ELVIS MARKET: One famous Nixon picture prominently displayed at the 
presidential library shows him posing in the Oval Office with an unusual 
visitor, Elvis Presley. An original of that picture, plus three small gifts the 
President gave Elvis, go on the auction block in Los Angeles on Monday. 
Fine-art auctioneers Butterfield & Butterfield estimate the picture's value at 
a minimum of $6,000. Priciest item: The federal drug agent's badge Nixon gave 
Elvis, valued at a minimum of $10,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
