<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA / ANTELOPE VALLEY; HELP SOUGHT TO IDENTIFY BODY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Los Angeles County coroner's office is looking for help from the public to 
identify the body of a woman with two tattoos found last month in a field 
between Sierra Highway and 10th Street East, south of Avenue R, authorities 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Her body was discovered June 22 by a young boy riding his bicycle, authorities 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 "Since then, she has simply been known as Jane Doe No. 30," said Scott 
Carrier, a coroner's office spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
 Medical examiners believe the woman stood about 5 feet tall, weighed about 95 
pounds and had brown hair and brown eyes. She had two tattoos -- one of a rose 
or bunch of roses about 1 1/2 inches in length on the inside of the left ankle, 
the other of a peacock with a vulture-like head and flowing tail feathers just 
above her right shoulder blade, Carrier said. 
</P>
<P>
 When she died, the woman was wearing black underwear, a multicolored halter 
top, blue jeans and tan and gold sandals that laced around her ankles. 
</P>
<P>
 The coroner's office has been unable to identify the woman because the body 
was decomposed, Carrier said. The cause of death has not been undetermined. 
</P>
