<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: CAMARILLO; EXPLOSION BURNS 3 UTILITY WORKERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TRACY WILSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Three Gas Co. employees were burned Wednesday when the gas line they were 
replacing in a Camarillo residential neighborhood exploded, fire officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Dave Schrader of Newbury Park, and Dan Neubauer and Chris Mallory, both of 
Simi Valley, suffered first- and second-degree burns as a result of the blast, 
which occurred about 3:10 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 All three were treated and released from Pleasant Valley Hospital, a nursing 
supervisor said. 
</P>
<P>
 The workers were connecting a new two-inch-wide plastic gas line near Lucero 
Street in Camarillo when the line exploded, fire and Gas Co. officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Gas Co. officials said they are investigating what triggered the explosion. 
</P>
<P>
 The men were working in a three-foot-deep hole in the street and bent over the 
pipe when it blew open, authorities said. All three suffered burns to their 
arms, fire officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 One of the men radioed for help after the explosion, and two Gas Co. crews 
working in the area arrived within minutes to shut off the gas line. 
</P>
<P>
 A concentrated flame from the blast rose about 20 feet in the air, fire 
officials said. The fire charred a neighbor's fence, but caused no other 
damage. Gas service to residents in the area was not affected, authorities 
said. TRACY WILSON 
</P>
</TEXT>
